        Chart Review 06/10/23


        [WARNING. THIS REVIEW MAY CYCLE INTO ONE OF THOSE FANBOY LOVE-INS YOU SEE ON THE INTERNET. TRY AND TAKE THIS WITH A PINCH OF SALT, BECAUSE I'M GONNA BE A LITTLE BIASED.]


        This week was ACR​ week. I could stop there, but let's keep going.

        If you were to pattern a guess as to WHO suffered, well, you only need to look at all of the huge falls taken by the long-running hits of the summer to come to a conclusion. Taylor Swift. Peggy Gou. Calvin Harris. Gunna. D.O.D. Charli XCX. THEY'VE ALL FALLEN. All of these hits are getting ended quicker than some of my college friendships. Which is saying a lot, coming from me.

        Doesn't affect the top end too much though. Doja Cat casually (barely) grabbing a 5th week at Numero Uno with Paint The Town Red, even though she probably wishes she hadn't. Not as if this is a complaint about the song, not at all, but you felt like she grabbed it at the death there. This has something to do with the fact that Doja Cat relinquished her Spotify title midweek to this week's runner-up. Poor old Kenya Grace, eh? Stuck with an absolute dog's dinner of a song that went viral on TikTok, and forced to be No.2 again this week. What went wrong? Nothing, obviously. She'll probably grab the top spot by Halloween, assuming the rise of Tate McRae (again) doesn't consume her hopes and dreams. She's certainly doing better than venbee, that's for sure.

        Now, naturally, the collapse of several of last week's big and mid hitters results in a number of songs flying up like tiny little rockets, ready to pierce the upper end of the charts with small, miniature impacts that grow into huge grievances. The likes of Miley Cyrus (groan), Billie Eilish, Florence + the Machine, SZA and Issey Cross suddenly reverse their reverses, and manoeuvre up a few incraments, but becoming the latest TikTok megahit is Water by Tyla. Ms. Seethal from Johannesburg and her R'N'B swellups have finally paid off, as the song creeps up to 10th place this week. Great for her and all, even though I wanted Asking by Sonny Fodera there instead. Still, there's always next week (bet it stays at 11).

        Billy Gillies also shoots into the Top 20 with his slightly-above-average floorfiller, whilst Mitski looks set to add her name to the list of 1-hit wonders (jk) as My Love All Mine All Mine staggers up, like, 20 places. Now all she needs to do is get her album back into the public eye, and Ed Sheeran-esque levels are assured.

        Speaking of that guy, it hasn't exactly been as right as rain for him this week. Putting out an album we'd barely heard last week turned out to be a double-edged sword for the most polarising man in Britain. On the soft side, it got to No.1 on the album chart like all the other ones, and it continues from where - left off in terms of SOUND and LYRICS and all those nouns my music teacher liked to repeat into my eardrums. But it's come at the cost of his precious chart positions.

        The 3 songs that have slipped in have only got to 27, 49 and 83, which would be reasonable for someone like Kylie (who falls to 8 on 'teh albumz'), but for him is ABSOLUTELY CATASTROPHIC. I know he didn't feel like promoting this one but come on, you're ED. You're known for bullying us into getting up Top 10 hits. What happened here!? Oh, and American Town is an alright song, but it could be better. Not like it's any matter to him, given he has yet another OCC award for his mantlepiece. Thinking about it, we haven't seen Doja Cat wield one yet, so maybe he could donate her one. Just a suggestion.

        American Town is one of 6+1 additions to the 40, that +1 being Rema who I hate. Moving on, and the endless nagging from the BTSARMY, countless remixes on iTunes, and the odd physical release or two have forced Jung Kook's latest effort 3D to gatecrash the Top 5. I mean, it's better than his last one, Jack Harlow does some pretty cool stuff on it, and he's clearly the break-out star of the K-POP KREW (is that even a thing), but songs like this are always gonna carry the stigma of being a little manipulated, and not of any deserving quality. I mean, his Spotify streams have been virtually nil compared to his rivals, and BTS fans notoriously abandon their songs after a week, so if you see him barely scraping the Top 20 next time out, erm... well....

        DON'T BE SURPRISED.

        Now then, what else is here, umm.. hmm.. give me a sec... Ooh! I know!

        (OMG THAT SONG BY JUNGLE HAZ HIT THE 40 BOYZ I'M SO HYPED THAT TOM MCFARLAND GUY GIVES ME SLIGHT TINGLES AND I WANT BUS YEARNIN' TATOOED ON MY BACKSIDE!!!?!)

        Now that we got that out the way, we can officially congratulate English collective Jungle on FINALLY breaking the Top 40, after 9 years and 4 albums of trying. Previously best known for Busy Earnin' which was seemingly on EVERY soundtrack in the world but only got to 158 (their best was the 94 effort of Time a few months later), they can scrub that albatross off their necks, as Back on 74 creeps up to 36 after 5 weeks of playing the hokey-cokey. It's joyous, it's jazzy (not that jazzy, fools), it's viral, AND it's incredible. Not the best song of 2023, obviously. There's about 20 other songs better than this. But this is definitely one for me to talk about at the end of the year.

        The other 3 hits could be forgiven for being swamped under the hype, but they all have something to talk about. At 34 is Troye Sivan who really wants to follow up Rush, doesn't he. Even though it's still there. His new one Got Me Started samples an old song, which immediately releagtes it to the bottom half of MY rankings, but you suddenly feel a little relieved that he's picked Shooting Stars from 2009. You know, that meme song? The one that goes BEEEEP-BE-BEEP, BE-B-BEEEEP-BE-BEEP? Yeah. That one. Song's kinda mid though.

        One place above it is the first Top 40 entry for the latest musical genre to grip us. PHONK. Supposedly inspired by Memphis rap and trap music, it's main purpose is to clog up TikToks as some sort of royalty-free music or whatever, but it's been making splashes for a litte while now. 'Songs' like Murder On My Mind, LONELY BUZZARDS, and METAMORPHOSIS have all graced the Top 100, but they are all bested by ecstasy by an act called SUICIDAL-IDOL, whom the only pictures I can find of her is an emo teen from 2006 (that's what it looks like anyway). 95 seconds long, it comes in a normal variant, and the slightly more-streamed slower version that's been doing the rounds, and at the end of all of that, it's just kinda mediocre. It also joins the long line of Top 40 songs that Radio 1 won't play, thus finally giving me an excuse to compare her to Richard Hawley. Remember Richard Hawley? He had a hit in 2007, but it didn't get played in full that day. Poor him. And poor SUICIDAL-IDOL. Imagine if it goes Top 10.

        Also new is the latest rap song no one cares about, Hide and Seek by a guy called 163Margs, who achieves a rare feat only a few new artists can ever do. Get a Top 40 hit with your first ever upload to Spotify. Doesn't make it good though, no matter how hard he and Digga D try to spice it up. Although it did get played on Radio 1 however, which kinda makes PHONK music look dead. Which it isn't.

        Also new are Noah Kanah, Dominic Fike and Blanco, PinkPantheress could've done better, whilst Jorja Smith's new LP charts at 3, yet doesn't spawn a song that can get higher than 50 at the present time. Could be worse. You could be Mae Muller, whose new album has flopped so hard you wonder why she represented us at Eurovision. No wonder the people that chose her and Sam Ryder before that have decided to abandon their post for 2024.

        And with that ends this page of action. See you next week for when Drake takes over the chart. For the 51,612th time.



        (P.S. blink-182 have done better than last time, as they only fall to 67. Campbell & Alcemist look most likely to grab a Top 40 placing next week with a song from 1998. And there are new remade albums from Roger Waters and Paramore to battle Drake next week. Only in 2023 could this stuff happen. ;) Might as well enjoy it before Mariah Carey comes back into our lives, eh?)
